---
layout: layouts/home.njk
title: Codex Logbook Variants
description: A few captain's log and timeline directions, all reading from markdown files in /logs/.
showPostHeader: false
permalink: /codex-logbook/
stylesheets:
  - /assets/css/codex-logbook.css
---

{% from "components/codex-logbook-feed.njk" import renderCodexLogbookNav with context %}

{% set logItems = collections.timeline | default([]) %}
{% set latestLog = (logItems | reverse | first) if logItems | length else null %}

<section class="codex-logbook-shell">
  <header class="codex-logbook-hero">
    <p class="codex-logbook-hero__eyebrow">Codex Preview Set</p>
    <h1 class="codex-logbook-hero__title">Captain's log pages with the same markdown underneath.</h1>
    <p class="codex-logbook-hero__copy">
      Every variant below reads from the same <code>/logs/</code> folder.
      The entries use front matter like posts or notes, while the body stays a short markdown snippet.
      I left the public route as <code>/codex-logbook/...</code> so you can pick a direction before committing to <code>/logs/</code> as the final list page.
    </p>

    <div class="codex-logbook-hero__stats">
      <div class="codex-logbook-stat">
        <span class="codex-logbook-stat__label">Source folder</span>
        <strong class="codex-logbook-stat__value">/logs/</strong>
      </div>
      <div class="codex-logbook-stat">
        <span class="codex-logbook-stat__label">Entries loaded</span>
        <strong class="codex-logbook-stat__value">{{ logItems | length }}</strong>
      </div>
      <div class="codex-logbook-stat">
        <span class="codex-logbook-stat__label">Latest sample</span>
        <strong class="codex-logbook-stat__value">{{ latestLog.data.title if latestLog else 'No logs yet' }}</strong>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  {{ renderCodexLogbookNav('overview') }}

  <section class="codex-logbook-preview-grid" aria-label="Logbook variants">
    <article class="codex-logbook-preview-card">
      <h2 class="codex-logbook-preview-card__title">Threaded Feed</h2>
      <p class="codex-logbook-preview-card__copy">
        The closest to a Twitter or Threads view.
        Compact identity row, stacked cards, and full markdown content visible inline.
      </p>
      <div class="codex-logbook-preview-card__actions">
        <a class="codex-logbook-preview-card__link" href="/codex-logbook/threaded/">Open threaded variant</a>
      </div>
      <p class="codex-logbook-preview-card__meta">Best if you want the most social-feed-like presentation.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="codex-logbook-preview-card">
      <h2 class="codex-logbook-preview-card__title">Bridge Console</h2>
      <p class="codex-logbook-preview-card__copy">
        More cinematic and naval.
        A left-hand rail, sticky time stamps, and cards that feel closer to a command-deck journal.
      </p>
      <div class="codex-logbook-preview-card__actions">
        <a class="codex-logbook-preview-card__link" href="/codex-logbook/bridge/">Open bridge variant</a>
      </div>
      <p class="codex-logbook-preview-card__meta">Best if you want "captain's log" to feel explicit and atmospheric.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="codex-logbook-preview-card">
      <h2 class="codex-logbook-preview-card__title">Archive Ledger</h2>
      <p class="codex-logbook-preview-card__copy">
        A sharper editorial layout with date columns and compact cards.
        Still scrollable like a feed, but more like an operations archive than a social app.
      </p>
      <div class="codex-logbook-preview-card__actions">
        <a class="codex-logbook-preview-card__link" href="/codex-logbook/archive/">Open archive variant</a>
      </div>
      <p class="codex-logbook-preview-card__meta">Best if you want the page to feel durable, indexed, and referenceable.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
</section>
